  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells serve several key functions in plants, primarily providing structural support. These cells are characterized by their thick, lignified cell walls, which make them rigid and strong. Here are some specific functions of sclerenchyma cells:\n\n1. **Structural Support**: Sclerenchyma cells help maintain the structural integrity of the plant. Their rigidity supports the plant body, particularly in areas that are subject to mechanical stress, such as stems and leaf veins.\n\n2. **Strength and Protection**: The lignified walls of sclerenchyma cells provide strength and protection to various parts of the plant. They form structures like fibers and sclereids, which contribute to the toughness of certain tissues.\n\n3. **Mechanical Support**: In many plants, sclerenchyma fibers run longitudinally and provide tensile strength, helping the plant withstand bending and stretching forces.\n\n4. **Conductive Functions**: Although not their primary role, certain forms of sclerenchyma can assist in conduction, for example, by supporting vascular bundles that transport water, nutrients, and sugars throughout the plant.\n\nOverall, sclerenchyma cells are essential for the physical stability and protection of plants, allowing them to grow upright and withstand various environmental stresses.",
